  <h2>Food Pairing Guide</h2>

<p>Bordeaux wines create exceptional food pairings through their structured tannins, balanced acidity, and complex flavor profiles. The key lies in understanding the <strong>flavor bridge concept</strong>—matching the wine's earthy minerality, dark fruit concentration, and herbaceous notes with complementary elements in food.</p>

<h3>Classic Regional Pairings</h3>
<p>Traditional Bordeaux cuisine offers time-tested combinations. <strong>Entrecôte à la Bordelaise</strong> exemplifies perfect harmony—the beef's richness balances Cabernet Sauvignon's tannins, while shallots and red wine reduction echo the wine's savory complexity. <strong>Côte de Boeuf</strong> with bone marrow amplifies this effect, as the marrow's unctuous texture softens aggressive tannins in young Bordeaux.</p>

<h3>Versatile Everyday Options</h3>
<ul class="bg-wine-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
<li><strong>Grilled lamb chops</strong> - The meat's natural gaminess complements Merlot's plush fruit while herbs bridge the wine's garrigue notes</li>
<li><strong>Mushroom risotto</strong> - Earthy porcini and cremini mushrooms mirror Bordeaux's forest floor characteristics, especially in Right Bank blends</li>
<li><strong>Aged hard cheeses</strong> - Comté or aged Gouda's crystalline texture and nutty flavors enhance the wine's mineral backbone</li>
<li><strong>Duck confit</strong> - The rich, rendered fat mellows tannins while the meat's savory depth matches the wine's complexity</li>
</ul>

<h3>Special Occasion Selections</h3>
<p><strong>Rack of lamb with herb crust</strong> represents the pinnacle of Bordeaux pairing—rosemary and thyme echo Cabernet Franc's herbaceous qualities, while the lamb's tender texture allows the wine's structure to shine. For celebrations, <strong>beef Wellington</strong> creates layers of flavor interaction: the pastry's richness, mushroom duxelles' earthiness, and beef's intensity all harmonize with aged Bordeaux's developed tertiary flavors.</p>

<p class="text-wine-700"><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Left Bank Bordeaux (Cabernet Sauvignon-dominant) pairs exceptionally with red meat and strong flavors, while Right Bank wines (Merlot-based) complement dishes with softer textures and more delicate preparations. The wine's vintage and aging also influence pairing success—younger Bordeaux needs heartier dishes to tame tannins, while mature bottles pair beautifully with subtle preparations that won't overshadow developed flavors.</p>

